{"@type":"Question","name":"Why did my bank freeze my account after I filed bankruptcy?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Banks freeze accounts after learning of a bankruptcy filing because they are required to turn over estate funds to the trustee under 11 U.S.C. section 542, while simultaneously avoiding violating the automatic stay under section 362. Rather than decide which funds belong to whom, they freeze the account and wait for the trustee to instruct them. Some banks (notably Wells Fargo) freeze all accounts over a low threshold as a matter of internal policy."}},
{"@type":"Question","name":"How long does a post-bankruptcy bank freeze last?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Typically 3 to 10 business days after the bank confirms the filing. Resolution requires either the trustee releasing a hold letter to the bank (for exempt funds), the trustee demanding turnover, or the bank verifying that account balances are below the trustee's interest threshold. Most freezes end within two weeks of filing."}},
{"@type":"Question","name":"Which banks are most likely to freeze accounts after a bankruptcy filing?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Wells Fargo has had the most litigation around routine post-filing freezes (see In re Mwangi and related cases). Chase, Bank of America, and US Bank freeze in some regions. Credit unions and smaller community banks generally do not freeze automatically. No federal rule requires the freeze - it is a bank-by-bank internal policy choice."}},
{"@type":"Question","name":"Is a post-filing freeze a violation of the automatic stay?",""+"acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Unsettled. Courts are split. The Ninth Circuit in Mwangi held that a routine administrative freeze by Wells Fargo violated section 362(a)(3). The Second and Sixth Circuits have been more permissive, treating short freezes as prudent compliance with section 542 turnover obligations. If your freeze extends beyond 10-14 days or prevents access to clearly exempt funds, consult your bankruptcy attorney about a stay-violation motion."}},
{"@type":"Question","name":"Should I move money out of my bank account before filing bankruptcy?",""+"acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Some attorneys advise moving funds to a credit union or smaller bank in the week before filing, to avoid the Wells Fargo / Chase routine-freeze pattern. This is legal - you are not hiding assets, just choosing where they sit. You must still disclose the account on your schedules. Do not close accounts without leaving a trail; do not withdraw cash and 'hide' it; those moves create trustee problems worse than a freeze."}}
]}
